title: SFH on obstetric services
content_text:
p>
    Following is the transcript of remarks (English portion) made by the 
    Secretary for Food and Health, Dr York Chow, after attending the Legislative 
    Council Health Services Panel meeting in the Legislative Council Complex 
    this morning (March 12): Reporter: (on amending the Basic Law to deter the problem of Mainland women 
    coming to Hong Kong to give birth) Secretary for Food and Health: The Government is very clear in terms of 
    whether we will interpret the Basic Law or amending the Basic Law. The

whether we will interpret the Basic Law or amending the Basic Law. The 
    present situation requires us to have administrative measures to ensure that 
    the number of Mainland women giving birth in Hong Kong is under control. So 
    far, we have been able to establish the quota system and also the various 
    measures to enable that the number of (Mainland) pregnant women giving birth 
    in Hong Kong is within our capacity. We are discussing the (delivery) quota 
    for next year. It is much more important to access, first of all, the

for next year. It is much more important to access, first of all, the 
    capacity situation. We are seeing an increasing trend of Hong Kong women 
    giving birth in Hong Kong. So the delivery quota (for Mainland pregnant 
    women) for next year will definitely be reduced. Reporter: (on delivery quota in 2013) Secretary for Food and Health: There is no quota for Hong Kong women. With 
    the same service capacity, it is expected the number of Mainland mothers
the same service capacity, it is expected the number of Mainland mothers giving birth in Hong Kong will be less than this year. (Please also refer to the Chinese portion of the transcript.)
